TECHNICAL AUDIT — psira-frontend (Angular 10)
[SEVERITY: CRITICAL] — Hardcoded Secret Key Exposed in Source Code
What's wrong:
A hardcoded symmetric encryption key (secretKey) is embedded in the environment configuration file and used client-side for encrypting sensitive data (patient records, user profiles) in URL query parameters.

Where exactly:

File: src/environments/environment.base.ts
Line: 15
Key: 'hfsdjfhdufhiuegewurge8365746543785643785638276423874'
Why it matters:
This key is exposed in the frontend bundle. Anyone can decrypt data encoded in URLs (e.g., /mhira/case-management/profile?profile=...), exposing patient PII (names, medical record numbers, contact details). Used in 21+ files including header.component.ts:68, patients-list.component.ts:141, patient-profile.component.ts, etc.

Fix:
Remove the hardcoded key from the frontend. Use server-side encryption with keys stored in a secure backend service, or use JWTs for session data instead of encoding user/patient objects in URLs.

[SEVERITY: CRITICAL] — XSS Vulnerability via noSanitize Pipe
What's wrong:
The application uses Angular's DomSanitizer.bypassSecurityTrustHtml() to render table cell content without sanitization, bypassing Angular's built-in XSS protection.

Where exactly:

File: src/app/@shared/pipes/nosanitize.pipe.ts
Lines: 7–9
Used in: src/app/@shared/components/table/table.component.html lines 189, 196
Why it matters:
If backend data contains malicious scripts (e.g., from a compromised database or user input), they will execute in other users' browsers. This is a known attack vector for session hijacking, credential theft, or malware distribution.

Fix:
Remove the noSanitize pipe entirely and use Angular's default sanitization. If HTML rendering is required, sanitize data on the server before sending it to the frontend.

[SEVERITY: HIGH] — Token Storage in localStorage (XSS-Accessible)
What's wrong:
JWT access and refresh tokens are stored in localStorage, which is accessible to any JavaScript running on the page.

Where exactly:

File: src/app/auth/login/login.component.ts
Lines: 41–48
typescript
localStorage.setItem('auth_app_token', JSON.stringify({
  accessToken: data.login.accessToken,
  refreshToken: data.login.refreshToken,
}));
Why it matters:
If the application has any XSS vulnerability (including via the noSanitize pipe above), attackers can steal tokens from localStorage and impersonate users. This is especially critical for a mental health application handling sensitive patient data.

Fix:
Use httpOnly cookies for token storage instead. The backend should set tokens as secure, httpOnly, SameSite=Strict cookies.

[SEVERITY: HIGH] — Silent Error Swallowing in Production
What's wrong:
HTTP errors are logged only in non-production mode. In production, errors are thrown without logging, making debugging impossible and hiding failures from monitoring.

Where exactly:

File: src/app/@core/http/error-handler.interceptor.ts
Lines: 23–29
typescript
private errorHandler(response: HttpEvent<any>): Observable<HttpEvent<any>> {
  if (!environment.production) {
    log.error('Request error', response);
  }
  throw response;
}
Why it matters:
Production issues become invisible. When API calls fail (network errors, 5xx errors, timeouts), there's no way to investigate. This directly impacts patient care workflows.

Fix:
Always log errors (to a proper logging service), and implement retry logic for transient failures. Never silently throw errors.

[SEVERITY: HIGH] — Missing Token Expiration Check
What's wrong:
The token expiration check is commented out in the authentication service. Tokens are treated as valid indefinitely.

Where exactly:

File: src/app/auth/auth.service.ts
Lines: 60–62
typescript
// const isExpired = check if token is expired
// return !isExpired;
Why it matters:
Stolen tokens remain valid forever. Users cannot be logged out remotely, and compromised sessions persist indefinitely.

Fix:
Implement proper JWT expiration checking on app initialization and on each API call.

[SEVERITY: MEDIUM] — Deprecated Angular 10 with Known CVEs
What's wrong:
The application runs Angular 10.0.14 (released 2020), which has multiple known security vulnerabilities and is no longer supported.

Where exactly:

File: package.json
Lines: 31–40
Why it matters:
Angular 10 has known CVEs (e.g., CVE-2020-28496, CVE-2021-2135) that will never be patched. The application is also missing performance improvements and modern browser features.

Fix:
Upgrade to Angular 17+ (LTS). This is a significant migration but critical for security.

[SEVERITY: MEDIUM] — No GraphQL Authentication Link
What's wrong:
The Apollo GraphQL client is configured without an authentication link. There's no mechanism to attach the Bearer token to GraphQL requests.

Where exactly:

File: src/app/graphql.module.ts
Lines: 9–14
The cache is created but no AuthLink or setContext adds the Authorization header.

Why it matters:
GraphQL requests may be unauthenticated if the REST interceptor is bypassed. This is a defense-in-depth failure.

Fix:
Add an Apollo middleware link that reads the token from localStorage (or cookies) and attaches it to GraphQL operations.

[SEVERITY: MEDIUM] — Multiple console.log in Production Code
What's wrong:
Multiple console.log statements exist in production components without environment guards.

Where exactly:

src/app/auth/login/login.component.ts:72 (console.log('notification clicked!'))
src/app/auth/login/login.component.ts:81 (console.log(error))
src/app/auth/login/login.component.ts:92 (console.log(error))
src/app/assessment-form/assessment-form.component.ts:94 (console.log(this.disclaimer))
Why it matters:
Console output can leak sensitive data in browser devtools and indicates missing proper logging infrastructure.

Fix:
Replace with proper logger service calls that respect the environment.

[SEVERITY: LOW] — Inefficient Data Processing in Assessment Form
What's wrong:
The assessment form uses nested loops with structuredClone and object transformations on every initialization.

Where exactly:

File: src/app/assessment-form/assessment-form.component.ts
Lines: 40–80
typescript
const assessment = structuredClone(oldAssessment);
for (const questionnaire of assessment.questionnaireAssessment.questionnaires) {
  questionnaire.questionGroups.map((group: any) => {
    // ... nested loops
  });
}
Why it matters:
For large questionnaires with many question groups, this causes unnecessary memory allocation and CPU usage on page load.

Fix:
Transform data on the server or use Angular's OnPush change detection with memoized selectors.

[SEVERITY: LOW] — Missing Return Type Annotations
What's wrong:
Many functions lack explicit return types, making the codebase harder to maintain and refactor safely.

Where exactly:
Common across: *.service.ts, *.component.ts

Fix:
Enable strictReturnTypes in TypeScript config and fix violations.

